---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Eclipse Safety Guide - Eclipse Central" description="Essential safety information for viewing solar and lunar eclipses safely without eye damage.">
  <article class="page-content">
    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>Eclipse Safety Guide</h1>
      <p class="page-intro">Protect your vision while experiencing the wonder of eclipses.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="warning-section">
      <div class="warning-box">
        <h2>‚ö†Ô∏è Critical Warning</h2>
        <p><strong>NEVER look directly at the Sun during a solar eclipse without proper protection.</strong> Even during an eclipse, the Sun's rays can cause permanent eye damage or blindness.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="safety-methods">
      <h2>Safe Viewing Methods</h2>
      
      <div class="method-grid">
        <div class="method-card safe">
          <h3>‚úÖ Eclipse Glasses</h3>
          <p>ISO 12312-2 certified eclipse glasses are the safest direct viewing method. Check for certification marks and inspect for damage before use.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="method-card safe">
          <h3>‚úÖ Welding Filters</h3>
          <p>Welding glass with shade 14 or darker provides safe direct viewing. Lighter shades are NOT safe.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="method-card safe">
          <h3>‚úÖ Pinhole Projection</h3>
          <p>Create a simple pinhole projector using cardboard or use the shadow of leaves to safely observe the eclipse indirectly.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="method-card unsafe">
          <h3>‚ùå Sunglasses</h3>
          <p>Regular sunglasses, even very dark ones, are NOT safe for looking at the Sun during an eclipse.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="method-card unsafe">
          <h3>‚ùå Smoked Glass</h3>
          <p>Smoked glass, exposed film, or CD/DVDs do NOT provide adequate protection.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="method-card unsafe">
          <h3>‚ùå Camera/Phone</h3>
          <p>Looking at the eclipse through a camera, telescope, or phone camera can concentrate harmful rays.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="totality-exception">
      <h2>üåë During Totality</h2>
      <p>Only during the brief moment of totality in a total solar eclipse can you safely look directly at the eclipse without protection. You must put protection back on immediately when totality ends.</p>
      
      <div class="totality-signs">
        <h3>Signs Totality is Ending:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>First bright flash of sunlight (diamond ring effect)</li>
          <li>Temperature starts to rise</li>
          <li>Shadow bands may appear again</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="lunar-safety">
      <h2>üåô Lunar Eclipse Safety</h2>
      <p>Lunar eclipses are completely safe to view with the naked eye, binoculars, or telescopes. No special protection is needed since you're looking at the Moon, not the Sun.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="emergency">
      <h2>üö® If You Accidentally Look</h2>
      <p>If you accidentally glance at the Sun during an eclipse:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Don't panic - brief accidental glances usually don't cause permanent damage</li>
        <li>Seek medical attention if you experience eye pain, vision changes, or seeing spots</li>
        <li>Contact an eye doctor immediately for professional evaluation</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
